yn Van / Goff, Rebecca / Lunak, S. Megan / Chatsis, Annabelle / Schupbach, Scott -- t100 years of analyzing Coeur d'Alene with the community / rBischoff, Shannon / Fountain, Amy / Vincent, Audra -- tCreating learning materials and teaching materials for language revitalization: The case of Mutsun / rWarner, Natasha / Geary, Quirina / Butler, Lynnika -- tCollaborative research and assessment in Kaqchikel / rHeaton, Raina / Xoyón, Igor -- tThe collaborative process in a Wounaan meu language documentation project / rRunk, Julie Velásquez / Opua, Chenier Carpio -- tBabanki literacy classes and community-based language research / rAkumbu, Pius W. -- tExploring new research perspectives on African cultures through language documentation / rMutaka, Philip -- tThe field is not the lab, and the lab is not the field: Experimental linguistics and endangered language communities / rMeyer, Joshua R. / Kloehn, Nicholas / Carnie, Andrew / Archangeli, Diana / Clayton, Ian / Fisher, Muriel / Hammond, Michael / Ussishkin, Adam / Warner, Natasha -- tTransforming the landscape of language revitalization work in Australia: The Documenting and Revitalising Indigenous Languages training model / rFlorey, Margaret -- tIndex  aThere has been an increasing interest in the emerging subfield within linguistics and anthropology often referred to as community-based research (Himmelmann 1998, Rice 2010, Crippen and Robinson 2013, among others). This volume brings together perspectives from academics, community members, and those that find themselves in both academia and the community. The volume begins with a working definition of the notions of community-based research as a practice and illustrates how such notions shifted, without abandoning the outlined tenets within the working definition, as the chapters developed to include notions of community-based research as a tool and ideology as well as an orientation. Each of the 17 chapters represents a case-study with the first five including discussions of broader issues and theoretical perspectives while exploring community-based research as an emerging subfield within linguistics. The case-studies comprise work from the Americas, Australia, India, Europe, and Africa. The goal of the volume is to build on the emerging literature and practices in the field to arrive at a better understanding of how community-based research is theorized and practiced in a variety of environments, communities, and cultures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Mrz 2018) 4aCommunity Engagement. 4aCommunity-based Research. 4aField Work.1 aBischoff, Shannon T., eeditor.1 aJany, Carmen, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2018 Englishz978311060407808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2018z9783110603170oZDB-23-DSP0 cEPUBz978-3-11-052481-90 cprintz978311052474140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110527018423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110527018.jpg  a978-3-11-060407-8  EBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060425-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishb2018  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aZDB-23-DGGb2017  aZDB-23-DSPb2018